Setup

Before introducing the exercises, we will need to make sure that the relevant data objects have been loaded.

de_treated <- readRDS("Robjects/de_treated.rds")
dds <- readRDS("Robjects/dds.rds")

Plotting multiple genes

The first exercise involves plotting the expression level of multiple genes. As we saw, plotCounts is only able to plot one gene.

The code to plot multiple genes is a bit more involved, and we will start by normalizing the counts. We do not usually need to perform this steps as it happens automatically when the DESeq function is run.

library(DESeq2)
dds <- estimateSizeFactors(dds)
using 'avgTxLength' from assays(dds), correcting for library size
count_matrix <- counts(dds, normalized=TRUE)

Next, we extract the ENSEMBL names of the top 10 most differentially-expressed genes.

library(dplyr)
my_genes <- results(de_treated,tidy=TRUE) %>% 
  arrange(padj) %>% 
  slice(1:10) %>% 
  pull(row)

As we saw, the count matrix is a numeric matrix rather than a data frame. We have to convert it into a data frame in order to use the standard dplyr tools. It does not have the gene names as a column and an easy way to add them is to use the rownames_to_column function in tibble.

count_matrix %>% data.frame %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("row") %>% 
  filter(row %in% my_genes)

The data are in the wrong format to be plotting in ggplot2, so need to be converted to long or "tidy format.

count_matrix %>% data.frame %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("row") %>% 
  filter(row %in% my_genes) %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(-row, names_to = "Run",values_to = "count")
NA

We would like to join this data with the meta data

sampleInfo <- data.frame(colData(dds))
sampleInfo

However, the Run column in our counts matrix has an X character before each name (e.g.X1_CTR_BC_2 rather than 1_CTR_BC_2). This is because column names in a numeric matrix are no allowed to begin with a number. We can use a function to replace the X with an empty character; effectively deleting the X.

count_matrix %>% data.frame %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("row") %>% 
  filter(row %in% my_genes) %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(-row, names_to = "Run",values_to = "count") %>% 
  mutate(Run = stringr::str_replace_all(Run, "X",""))

The count data can now be joined with the sample information to create a data frame ready for plotting in ggplot2.

plot_data <- count_matrix %>% data.frame %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("row") %>% 
  filter(row %in% my_genes) %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(-row, names_to = "Run",values_to = "count") %>% 
  mutate(Run = stringr::str_replace_all(Run, "X","")) %>%
  left_join(sampleInfo)
Joining, by = "Run"

Exercise: Produce a plot to show the normalised counts for the 10 most differentially-expressed genes in the various treatments. See below for an example

The geom_jitter geom can be used to add random noise to the x-axis, and adjusting the width argument gives a better placement of points.

With facet_wrap we can create a grid of plots for each gene. The additional argument scales="free_y" can be helpful as the genes will have different underlying expression level.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = condition,y = count)) + geom_jitter(width=0.1) + facet_wrap(~row,scales="free_y") + xlab("Treatment") + ylab("Normalised Counts")

The code may seem quite complicated, but it can be adjusted to plot other genes. When we create the plot_data object we can change the my_genes to be any set of ENSEMBL IDs that we are interested in. For example, we could plot all the genes from a particular pathway provided that we know the ENSEMBL IDs.

plot_data <- count_matrix %>% data.frame %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("row") %>% 
  filter(row %in% my_genes) %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(-row, names_to = "Run",values_to = "count") %>% 
  mutate(Run = stringr::str_replace_all(Run, "X","")) %>%
  left_join(sampleInfo)

Analysing a subset of data, or using a multi-factor analysis

As we saw in the workshop, it is possible to analyse a subset of the data, or to employ a multi-factor model to correct for technical differences in the data.

Exercise: In the colData we have a record of the replicate number. Lets suppose you found out there was an issue with set of replicates numbered 1. How would you create a subset of dds to analyse replicates 2 and 3?

The replicate information can be obtained using:-

dds$Replicate
[1] 1 1 1 2 2 2 3 3 3

A logical vector can be created to indicate which samples belong to replicates 2 or 3.

## either of these will work
dds$Replicate == 2 | dds$Replicate == 3
[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE
dds$Replicate != 1
[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE

The DESeqDataSet object dds respects the standard matrix subset operations in R, so to subset to replicates 2 and 3 we can use the following

dds_new <- dds[,dds$Replicate != 1]

Exercise: We can use a multi-factor design to correct for technical factors (batch, gender, cell-line) that influence our data, but we are not interested in comparing. How would you create a design to compare the condition variable, but correct for Replicate. You do not have to run the analysis.

The use of multi-factor designs is explored in the DESeq2 vignette

  • https://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/vignettes/DESeq2/inst/doc/DESeq2.html#multi-factor-designs

The design in our case is as follows, where Replicate is the factor in our data that we are not interested in, but we want to compare condition.

design(dds) <- ~Replicate + condition

Annotation Packages

The example dataset we have been looking at comes from human samples - so we used the package org.Hs.eg.db. However, how would we proceed if analysing mouse data.

Exercise:

Take a look at the Bioconductor list of packages.

  • https://bioconductor.org/packages/release/BiocViews.html#___AnnotationData

  • Which package would you use to annotate mouse RNA-seq data? Zebrafish data?

  • Using the org.Hs.eg.db package, what Gene Ontology (GO) term do the genes COL1A1, COL1A2 and COL3A1 belong to?

The packages org.Mm.eg.db and org.Dr.eg.db are the equivalent packages for Mouse and Zebrafish. The installation code is as follows

BiocManager::install("org.Mm.eg.db")
BiocManager::install("org.Dr.eg.db")

The select function can be used to interrogate the org.Hs.eg.db database. We can avoid confusion with the select function from dplyr using the code AnnotationDbi::select.

The IDs we want to find more information about are of the SYMBOL keytype.

library(org.Hs.eg.db)
AnnotationDbi::select(org.Hs.eg.db, 
                      keys = c("COL1A1","COL1A2","COL3A1"),
                      keytype = "SYMBOL",
                      columns = "GO")
